    <h1>Play tourist at home</h1>
    <h2>Ex&#xAD;plore the whole of Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore with young chil&#xAD;dren and avoid crowds at the same time</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Soh Wee Ling stlife@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;A for&#xAD;mer tax con&#xAD;sul&#xAD;tant,&#xD;&#xA;Soh Wee Ling is a free&#xAD;lance writer and pho&#xAD;tog&#xAD;ra&#xAD;pher who is back in Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore af&#xAD;ter more than 10 years abroad. She is mar&#xAD;ried to a French&#xAD;man and they have two chil&#xAD;dren &#x2013; Elna, four, and Llu&#xAD;cia, nine</span>
    </section>

    <p>The past months haven’t been easy.</p>
    <p>Like many other fam­i­lies, we have been stuck mostly at home, with­out help from grand­par­ents or helpers – and with a new­born.</p>
    <p>As the pan­demic con­tin­ues to loom, we have changed the way we go out, care­ful to avoid malls and crowded venues on week­ends.</p>
    <p>Also, since we are trapped in Sin­ga­pore for the time be­ing, we are mak­ing the most of it.</p>
    <p>For par­ents who would like to ex­plore Sin­ga­pore with young chil­dren while still avoid­ing crowds, here are some tried-and-tested itin­er­ar­ies good for half a day.</p>
    <p>Each itin­er­ary in­cludes sug­gested ac­tiv­i­ties that are in­ter­est­ing for old and young, with ca­sual din­ing op­tions for lunch or an early din­ner thrown in.</p>

